INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

Cricket packs a canvas kit bag on the workbench, item by item off a handwritten list: logbook, slide rule, a zippo, a folded photograph he doesn't look at.

Headlights swing across the wall. A truck door. Then DANNY in the barn doorway, keys still in his hand.

He looks at the simulator. At the orange SCRAP stencil. At the kit bag.

DANNY:
I know what's in the barn, Dad. I've known a year. I figured you'd tell me when it mattered.

Cricket zips the bag halfway and stops.

DANNY:
I'm not going to say any of the things. About your age, or the law, or Mom. You'd just stand there and let me finish.

CRICKET:
I would.

Danny looks at the logbook shelf — the fifty years of it — and back at his father. Whatever he came to say next, he doesn't say it.

DANNY:
You need a driver?

CRICKET:
Thursday. Four a.m. Dress like a farmer.

DANNY:
I am a farmer.

He goes. Cricket zips the bag the rest of the way.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, BEDROOM - NIGHT

The kit bag open on the bed. Cricket repacks it alone. Rolls each item tight, wedges them square.

He picks up two pairs of socks, starts to say something out loud from fifty years of habit — "You'll want the—" — and stops, mid-word, because there's nobody left in the room to finish it for him.

He takes the good ones. Not the gray. They've quit.

Presses the lid flat with both hands, testing the pack of it. His thumb catches on something — a seam in the canvas, raised slightly, old thread, three sides of small even stitches, not his own work.

He works it open careful with a pocketknife and shakes out what's inside: one dried, flattened zinnia, orange, gone thin as paper.

He doesn't know when she did this. Doesn't try to work out when.

He folds the canvas back over it, careful as he found it, and packs the rest of the bag around it.

INT. ALVAREZ KITCHEN, EAST LOS ANGELES - NIGHT

A small kitchen, saints on the wall, an old Singer on its own table by the window.

LITA, 80s, and Tito stand on opposite sides of the kitchen table. Between them, spread the table's whole length, a hand-sewn flag, fifty-one stars in the field, one more than it should carry.

They fold it together. Lengthwise. Lengthwise again. Then Lita starts the triangle folds from her end, tight and sharp, turning the colors over and over into themselves while Tito keeps the tension, and neither of them says one word.

The last fold tucks. A triangle of stars, packed tight.

Lita holds it a moment. Then she takes a small SAINT CHRISTOPHER medal on a pin from her apron pocket and pins it deep inside the last fold, where it will touch nothing but flag.

She puts the triangle in Tito's hands.

He kisses her forehead. Takes his cap off the chair, and goes. Through the window, under the streetlight, he sets the triangle on the truck seat with both hands.

Lita sits back down at the Singer and turns off the lamp.

CUT TO:
